<subSubSection pageId="71" pageNumber="72" type="remarks">
<paragraph pageId="71" pageNumber="72">Based on species AUS-01 of F.C. Thompson, in prep.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="71" pageNumber="72" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph pageId="71" pageNumber="72">Diagnosis.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="71" pageNumber="72">Basoflagellomere strongly widened, more or less triangular. Arista pilose.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="71" pageNumber="72" type="discussion">
<paragraph pageId="71" pageNumber="72">Discussion.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="71" pageNumber="72">
This species has first been recognized as undescribed by Dr. F.C. Thompson, who is preparing a description of it. As the species posesses some unique characters not found in any other species of 
<taxonomicName lsidName="" pageId="71" pageNumber="72" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Microdontinae">Microdontinae</taxonomicName>
, the present authors feel that it belongs in a new genus. These characters are: basoflagellomere strongly widened and more or less triangular; arista pilose; phallus dorsobasally with long projection; epandrium with dorsolateral ridge. Other interesting characters are the undeveloped mouthparts (shared with 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Masarygus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Masarygus" order="Diptera" pageId="71" pageNumber="72" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Masarygus</taxonomicName>
) and the lateral carinae on the face.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="71" pageNumber="72" type="distribution">
<paragraph pageId="71" pageNumber="72">Diversity and distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="71" pageNumber="72">Described species: 1. Australia (Queensland).</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
